Basic Usage

Source: vignettes/basics.Rmd
basics.Rmd

Example of a signature

Here we define our signature of interest as a group of genes randomly sampled from the estrogen-dependent gene expression geneset. A signature is simply a vector of symbols.

signatures <- readRDS(system.file("extdata/signatures.rds", package="hypeR"))
signature <- signatures$signature
head(signature)
#> [1] "GTF2F1"    "HIST1H2AJ" "KANK1"     "STAG1"     "FKBP4"     "SMC1A"

Example of a geneset

Here we use a genesets example from REACTOME. A geneset is simply a list of vectors, therefore, one can use any custom geneset in their analyses, as long as it is appropriately defined.

gsets <- readRDS(system.file("extdata/gsets.rds", package="hypeR"))
gsets <- gsets$REACTOME
head(names(gsets))
#> [1] "REACTOME_3_UTR_MEDIATED_TRANSLATIONAL_REGULATION"                        
#> [2] "REACTOME_A_TETRASACCHARIDE_LINKER_SEQUENCE_IS_REQUIRED_FOR_GAG_SYNTHESIS"
#> [3] "REACTOME_ABACAVIR_TRANSPORT_AND_METABOLISM"                              
#> [4] "REACTOME_ABC_FAMILY_PROTEINS_MEDIATED_TRANSPORT"                         
#> [5] "REACTOME_ABCA_TRANSPORTERS_IN_LIPID_HOMEOSTASIS"                         
#> [6] "REACTOME_ABORTIVE_ELONGATION_OF_HIV1_TRANSCRIPT_IN_THE_ABSENCE_OF_TAT"
head(gsets[[1]])
#> [1] "EIF1AX" "EIF2S1" "EIF2S2" "EIF2S3" "EIF3A"  "EIF3B"

Hyper enrichment

All workflows begin with performing hyper enrichment with hypeR. Often weâ€™re just interested in a single signature, as described above. In this case, hypeR will return a hyp object. This object contains relevant information to the enrichment results and is recognized by downstream methods.

hyp_obj <- hypeR(signature, gsets, fdr=0.05)
print(hyp_obj)
#> hyp object: 
#>   data: 73 x 8
#>   args: symbols
#>         gsets
#>         gsets_relational
#>         bg
#>         min_drawsize
#>         pval_cutoff
#>         fdr_cutoff
#>         verbose
hyp_df <- hyp_obj$as.data.frame()
print(hyp_df[5:10,1:4])
#>                                        pval     fdr set.annotated set.size
#> REACTOME_RNA_POL_I_TRANSCRIPTION    1.9e-33 2.6e-31            22      100
#> REACTOME_RNA_POL_I_PROMOTER_OPENING 4.1e-33 4.6e-31            20      100
#> REACTOME_CHROMOSOME_MAINTENANCE     8.8e-32 8.5e-30            23      100
#> REACTOME_PACKAGING_OF_TELOMERE_ENDS 2.8e-31 2.4e-29            18      100
#> REACTOME_AMYLOIDS                   3.4e-30 2.6e-28            20      100
#> REACTOME_MEIOTIC_RECOMBINATION      7.6e-30 5.1e-28            20      100

Show an interactive table

hyp_show(hyp_obj, simple=FALSE, stylish=TRUE)

Set background population size

Because genomic experiments often vary in the number of genes probed, itâ€™s important to be able to adjust the background population size accordingly, to ensure accurate enrichment statistics.

hyp_obj <- hypeR(signature, gsets, bg=10000, fdr=0.05)

Specify a background population of genes

In cases where the background population is small it is advisable to first reduce genesets to their intersection with the background population of genes. By providing a vector of background genes instead of an integer, hypeR will do just that. Here is an example of an experiment that only uses sex-linked genes and therefore genesets are restricted to just those included in the background population.

url = "https://www.genenames.org/cgi-bin/download/custom?col=gd_app_sym&chr=X&chr=Y&format=text"
r <- httr::GET(url)
text <- httr::content(r, "text", encoding="ISO-8859-1")
text.split <- strsplit(text, "\n")[[1]]
bg <- text.split[2:length(text.split)]
head(bg)
#> [1] "ABCB7"  "ABCD1"  "ACE2"   "ACOT9"  "ACSL4"  "ACTBP1"
hyp_obj <- hypeR(signature, gsets, bg=bg, fdr=0.05)

Save results to excel

hyp_to_excel(hyp_obj, file_path="pathways.xlsx")

Save results to table

hyp_to_table(hyp_obj, file_path="pathways.txt")
